Implementation of Minimax Search, Alpha-Beta Search, Heuristic Alpha-Beta Search and Monte-Carlo Tree Search
Objective

The objective of this question is to implement and compare four important AI search algorithms used in game playing and decision making:

Minimax Search
Alpha-Beta Pruning
Heuristic Alpha-Beta Search
Monte-Carlo Tree Search (MCTS)
Minimax Search

Minimax is an adversarial search algorithm used in two-player games. It assumes that both players play optimally.

Working:
MAX player tries to maximize the score.
MIN player tries to minimize the score.
The game tree is explored until terminal states are reached.
The best move is selected based on utility values.
Advantages
Guarantees optimal move.
Suitable for deterministic games.
Disadvantages
Large search space.
High computational cost.
Alpha-Beta Pruning

Alpha-Beta pruning is an optimization of Minimax.

Working
Alpha represents the best value that MAX can guarantee.
Beta represents the best value that MIN can guarantee.
Branches that cannot affect the final decision are pruned.
Advantages
Produces same result as Minimax.
Faster than Minimax.
Explores fewer nodes.
Heuristic Alpha-Beta Search

In large games it is impossible to search the entire tree.

Working
Search is limited to a fixed depth.
Heuristic evaluation function estimates board quality.
Alpha-Beta pruning is applied to reduce computations.
Advantages
Faster search.
Can handle large game trees.
Practical for real-world games.
Monte-Carlo Tree Search (MCTS)

MCTS uses random simulations to estimate the quality of moves.

Phases
1.Selection
2.Expansion
3.Simulation (Rollout)
4.Backpropagation
Advantages
1.Handles very large search spaces.
2.Used in modern game-playing AI.
3.Does not require handcrafted evaluation functions.
Applications
Chess
Go
Tic-Tac-Toe
Strategic planning
